ry secrets, and intelligence-the author relates true stories of colorful "professors of secrets" and clandestine encounters. In the process Jütte examines how our current notion of secrecy is radically different in this era of WikiLeaks, Snowden, et al., as opposed to centuries earlier when the truest, most important knowledge was generally considered to be secret by definition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aAlchemyxHistoryxEurope. 0aAlchemyzEuropexHistory. 0aJewish alchemistsxHistoryxEuropexEurope. 0aJewish alchemistszEuropexHistory. 0aJewish magicxHistory. 0aMystery. 0aOccultismxHistoryxEurope. 0aOccultismzEuropexHistory. 0aSecrecyxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aSecrecyxReligious aspectsxJudaismxHistory. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh1 aRiemer, Jeremiah08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213423423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300213423.jpg  a978-3-11-067250-3  YUP eBook Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO